
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `loadunimap` baraye bargozari yek table Unimap (Unicode Map) be console estefade mishavad. In dastoor be shoma komak mikonad ta namayesh character-haye Unicode ra dar terminal-e khod moratab konid.  Agar console-e shoma az Unicode poshtibani nemikonad, `loadunimap` yek payame khata neshon midahad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `loadunimap <file>` --> 📂 File Unimap ra bargozari mikonad.
    🔹 `loadunimap -v <file>` --> 💬 File Unimap ra bargozari mikonad va etela'ate bishtar neshon midahad (verbose).
    🔹 `loadunimap -C <console>` --> 🖥️ Console ra moshakhas mikonad (agar bishtar az yek console darid).

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ loadunimap /usr/share/consolefonts/iso02r.uni

    🔹 Table Unimap ra az file `iso02r.uni` bargozari mikonad.

    $ loadunimap -v /usr/share/consolefonts/iso02r.uni

    🔹 Table Unimap ra az file `iso02r.uni` bargozari mikonad va payam-haye afzudeyi neshon midahad.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ loadunimap /usr/share/consolefonts/def.uni
    Loading unimap

    🔹 Dastoor bala table Unimap pishfarz ra bargozari mikonad, va terminal shoma be dorosti character-haye Unicode ra namayesh khahad dad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `loadunimap` command is used to load a Unimap (Unicode Map) table into the console. This command helps you configure the display of Unicode characters in your terminal. If your console does not support Unicode, `loadunimap` will display an error message.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `loadunimap <file>` --> 📂 Loads the Unimap file.
    🔹 `loadunimap -v <file>` --> 💬 Loads the Unimap file and displays more information (verbose).
    🔹 `loadunimap -C <console>` --> 🖥️ Specifies the console to load the Unimap into (if you have multiple consoles).

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ loadunimap /usr/share/consolefonts/iso02r.uni

    🔹 Loads the Unimap table from the `iso02r.uni` file.

    $ loadunimap -v /usr/share/consolefonts/iso02r.uni

    🔹 Loads the Unimap table from the `iso02r.uni` file and displays additional messages.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ loadunimap /usr/share/consolefonts/def.uni
    Loading unimap

    🔹 The above command loads the default Unimap table, and your terminal should correctly display Unicode characters.
